Furthermore, we may assume both $\lambda,\,\mu >\frac{1}{2}$,
because, otherwise the off-diagonal blocks would be zero and
the state would be both separable and completely extendable. Using inequality
(\ref{eq:1.3}) and Theorem \ref{cu:B}, we conclude that
$S_\rho$ is a Gaussian covariance matrix if and only if
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\mu I_2 + \frac{\imath}{2} J_2\right) & \ge &
\begin{bmatrix} \alpha & 0 \\ 0 & -\beta \end{bmatrix}
\left(\lambda I_2 +\frac{\imath}{2}J_2\right)^{-1}
\begin{bmatrix} \alpha & 0 \\ 0 & -\beta \end{bmatrix} \\
&=& \frac{1}{\lambda^2 -\frac{1}{4}} \begin{bmatrix} \lambda
\alpha^2 & \frac{\imath}{2} \alpha \beta \\
-\frac{\imath}{2} \alpha \beta & \lambda \beta^2
\end{bmatrix}\\
&=& \begin{bmatrix} \alpha^2 \delta & \frac{\imath}{2}
\frac{\alpha\beta \delta}{\lambda} \\ -\frac{\imath}{2}
\frac{\alpha\beta \delta}{\lambda} & \beta^2 \delta
\end{bmatrix} \qquad \text{ where } \delta =
\frac{\delta}{\lambda^2 -\frac{1}{4}} 
\end{eqnarray*}

